  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These establish common standards and frameworks for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigations and prosecutions\n- Share evidence and financial intelligence\n- Extradition of suspects across borders\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement international anti-money laundering (AML) standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n\n4. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Countries align their domestic laws with international standards\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering offenses\n- Similar due diligence and reporting requirements\n\n5. Information Sharing Mechanisms\n- Interpol and Europol databases\n- Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs)\n- Cross-border collaboration in tracking financial crimes\n\n6. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International pressure on non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Economic sanctions for inadequate AML frameworks\n- Targeted financial restrictions\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multi-layered approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering globally.",
